  "faq_items": [
    {
      "q": "Is colonial a popular style in Florida?",
      "a": "Less common than craftsman or modern farmhouse, but still well-represented in older Florida neighborhoods (St. Augustine, Coral Gables, certain Jacksonville and Tampa suburbs). Florida's hurricane-resistance requirements make pure brick-clad colonials less common than their northern equivalents."
    },
    {
      "q": "What roof pitch works for colonial?",
      "a": "Steep, typically 8:12 to 10:12. The visible roof plane is part of the facade balance; flatter roofs make the house look top-heavy."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does brown work for colonial?",
      "a": "On colonial specifically, yes -- the warm tonal family of the roof reinforces the style's traditional palette. Brown asphalt is one of the most architecturally honest choices for revival-era styles in Florida."
    },
    {
      "q": "Will brown shingles fade more than gray?",
      "a": "Slightly less visibly. Brown drifts slightly warmer and slightly desaturated over 10 to 15 years of Florida UV. The shift is uniform, so the roof never develops the patchy look that aged gray shingles sometimes show. Source: NRCA Asphalt Shingle Manual."
    },
    {
      "q": "How do these renders compare to a real colonial home with that roof?",
